In order to carry out a quantitative analysis, the theoretically computed normalised images of the dopant wave functions are compared directly to the experimental images (similarly normalised) by computing the two comparator parameters described as follows: A direct comparison of images is performed by defining pixel-by-pixel difference comparator $C_{\rm P}$, where the difference of the experimental image pixels ($I_{\rm exp}(x,y)$) and the theoretical image pixels ($I_{\rm th}(x,y)$) is computed across the identical scanned areas ($A_{\rm scan}$=$N_x \times N_y$, where $N_x$ and $N_y$ are the total numbers of pixels along the $x$ and $y$ directions) and normalised by the total intensity of the experimental image, $i.e.$:

text:
\begin{equation}
C_{\rm P} = 1 - \left( \frac{\sum \limits_{x,y}^{N_x,N_y} |I_{\rm exp}(x,y) - I_{\rm th}(x,y) |}{\sum \limits_{x,y}^{N_x,N_y} I_{\rm exp}(x,y)} \right)
